      Funding secured
   =20
 =20

The whole trial is very weird? The basic situation is that the judge  has a=
lready ruled that Musk=E2=80=99s tweet that he had =E2=80=9Cfunding secured=
=E2=80=9D was false, and that he made this false statement recklessly. So t=
he trial =E2=80=94=C2=A0in this lawsuit about whether Musk committed securi=
ties fraud =E2=80=94 is only for the jury to whether his tweets were materi=
al to investors, whether they relied on those tweets, stuff like that. Thos=
e strike me as somewhat technical questions of securities class action law =
that would be hard and annoying for a jury to decide, whereas it would be r=
easonable to ask a jury =E2=80=9Cwell, did he have funding secured, or what=
?=E2=80=9D But the actual trial is the opposite: The jury rules on question=
s of materiality, but the question of whether Musk=E2=80=99s tweets were fa=
lse is already settled.
  [2]

Reasonably, nobody is acting like that, and Musk testified that he  really =
did have funding secured:

Elon Musk said he had funding to take Tesla Inc. private when he floated th=
e idea in 2018, saying that financing from Saudi Arabia=E2=80=99s sovereign=
-wealth fund and his own stake in rocket-company SpaceX would have provided=
 sufficient capital.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWith the SpaceX stock alone, I felt funding was secured,=E2=80=9D =
Mr. Musk said Monday in his second day on the stand in a case brought by in=
vestors who say they lost money because of his tweets proposing to take the=
 car company private.=C2=A0
Mr. Musk met with representatives of Saudi Arabia=E2=80=99s sovereign-wealt=
h fund, the Public Investment Fund, in late July 2018, a week before floati=
ng the possibility of taking Tesla private. A specific price for taking Tes=
la private wasn=E2=80=99t discussed at that meeting, nor was there a signed=
 document, Mr. Musk testified. Nevertheless, Mr. Musk said he walked away f=
rom the meeting thinking it was a =E2=80=9Cdone deal.=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CThe thing that was really, absolutely unequivocal was that they we=
re absolutely supportive of taking Tesla private,=E2=80=9D he said.

Look, we all   made fun of this at the time, and certainly=C2=A0I=C2=A0woul=
d not say that I had funding secured if I hadn=E2=80=99t discussed=C2=A0the=
 amount of funding or the price=C2=A0with my financing source. I=E2=80=99m =
not really going to=C2=A0disagree=C2=A0with the judge=E2=80=99s, and the SE=
C=E2=80=99s, conclusion that the =E2=80=9Cfunding secured=E2=80=9D claim wa=
s false.
I will say, though, that I had the same reaction to Musk=E2=80=99s plans to=
 take Twitter Inc. private last year. When he proposed to buy Twitter, back=
 in April, I wrote a column titled =E2=80=9CSure Elon Musk Might Buy Twitte=
r,=E2=80=9D saying:
I imagine that=C2=A0Twitter's bankers at Goldman Sachs will sit down with M=
usk's bankers at Morgan Stanley and Goldman will say =E2=80=9Cso uh where's=
 the financing coming from=E2=80=9D and Morgan Stanley will say =E2=80=9Coh=
 the financing is in this can=E2=80=9D and hand Goldman a can and Goldman w=
ill open the can and a bunch of fake snakes will pop out. =E2=80=9CAAAHHH,=
=E2=80=9D Goldman will scream, and then they will chuckle and=C2=A0say =E2=
=80=9Coh Elon, you got us again=E2=80=9D and everyone will have a good laug=
h. Because, again, uniquely among public-company CEOs, Elon Musk has in the=
 past pretended he was going to take a public company private with pretend =
financing! I am not saying that he=E2=80=99s joking now; I am just saying h=
e=E2=80=99s the only person who has ever made this particular joke in the p=
ast.
And then   like a=C2=A0week later Musk showed up with signed commitment let=
ters for $46.5 billion in financing, with roughly half of it coming from hi=
s own personal wealth and the rest coming from reputable banks. And then he=
 really did buy Twitter, for cash. Shows what I know! I still think he was =
joking in 2018, but he more or less was not joking in 2022, and, you know, =
that=E2=80=99s a data point. Musk is very rich, has a lot of devoted fans, =
and has a good track record of tapping them for money. If he wants to spend=
 a few tens of billions of dollars on something, he can probably find the m=
oney.
That was much=C2=A0less=C2=A0true in 2018 =E2=80=94=C2=A0when Tesla was wor=
th about $60 billion (it was over $1 trillion when he started on Twitter, t=
hough it=E2=80=99s less now), when Musk was not the richest person in the w=
orld (as he was before Twitter though, again, not now), when SpaceX was not=
   worth $140 billion, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but even then, Musk was already =
Musk. He was a pretty good pitchman. Could he have raised the $60 billion o=
r so needed to take Tesla private? Maybe? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s  Dana Hull re=
ported from his testimony yesterday:

Musk says he=E2=80=99s raised =E2=80=9Cmore money than anyone in history by=
 a significant margin=E2=80=9D because investors =E2=80=9Ctrust me to be tr=
uthful and responsible with their money.=E2=80=9D
Musk says he=E2=80=99s raised over $100 billion in total.

And today:
Musk says that =E2=80=9Cevery financing round I=E2=80=99ve ever done=E2=80=
=9D has been oversubscribed.=C2=A0
Well, I do recall reading last month about a   supposed financing round at =
Musk=E2=80=99s newly private Twitter, where he was going to go out and rais=
e money at the same $44 billion-ish valuation he agreed to in April. That s=
eemed improbable, and I haven=E2=80=99t heard about it since, suggesting th=
at maybe it was not oversubscribed?
I guess this all has nothing really to do with the lawsuit, since (1) he ha=
d not raised the financing to buy Twitter when he tweeted that he had and (=
2) he never actually did. But really his position is that he tweeted that h=
e was=C2=A0considering=C2=A0taking Tesla private, and that if he=C2=A0did=
=C2=A0end up deciding to take it private then financing would not be a prob=
lem. We can=E2=80=99t really know if that=E2=80=99s true, because the condi=
tion was never satisfied. But it seems like it might be.

