   =20
      Does Elon Musk know how mergers work?
   =20
 =20

Two small points on Musk=E2=80=99s testimony. First, here is  the Financial=
 Times:
Nicholas Porritt, a lawyer for shareholders, pointed out Musk did not discu=
ss any proposal in advance with Tesla=E2=80=99s board of directors. But the=
 billionaire said that would be improper: =E2=80=9CI, as the bidder, am not=
 allowed to have detailed discussions with the board because it represents =
the counterparty. So, it would be collusion if I discussed in detail with t=
he board.=E2=80=9D
This is a weird view? Most management buyouts begin with the chief executiv=
e officer approaching the board of directors and suggesting a deal, and dis=
cussions get pretty far along before there is a public announcement. (Also,=
 back in August 2018,  Musk said=C2=A0that he had had discussions with the =
board about his proposal, including the price and financing, before tweetin=
g it.) It=E2=80=99s not collusion to negotiate a deal with a counterparty; =
it=E2=80=99s just =E2=80=A6=C2=A0negotiation. That said, you can understand=
 his instinct that there is something weird and conflicted about the CEO of=
 a public company negotiating with its board to buy it for himself. It happ=
ens, fairly often, but it is a necessarily sensitive situation. He=E2=80=99=
s not wrong that, in some sense, it is=C2=A0good=C2=A0disclosure to give sh=
areholders some early warning about what is going on. It is just not tradit=
ional.
Second, here is  Dan Primack at Axios this morning:
[Musk] also reiterated his odd view of due diligence, as evidenced througho=
ut the Twitter saga, in claiming that the Saudis didn't need to do any prio=
r to Musk making a formal takeover offer because Tesla was a public company=
 (i.e., it already had access to all the information it would need).
I want to defend Musk a little bit here. Yes, this is absolutely an=C2=A0od=
d=C2=A0view of due diligence. Most people, in the course of doing or fundin=
g $60 billion leveraged buyouts, want to do some non-public due diligence o=
n the target company. They want to look at its financial plans and talk to =
its customers and employees and read its contracts and generally understand=
 the company in more depth than they could get from its public filings.
But it is not unheard-of to buy a public company without due diligence.=C2=
=A0In particular, if you are going to make a=C2=A0hostile=C2=A0takeover off=
er for a company =E2=80=94=C2=A0by taking a tender offer directly to shareh=
olders instead of negotiating with the board of directors =E2=80=94=C2=A0yo=
u have to be willing to do it without any cooperation from existing managem=
ent.
  [3]
 That is what Musk proposed to Twitter, and while the deal ultimately becam=
e friendly, he never did do due diligence. Also it makes sense! He followed=
 up by getting rid of 80% of employees, torching Twitter=E2=80=99s advertis=
ing business, unplugging data centers, selling the office espresso machines=
, etc. In a sense he bought Twitter to own=C2=A0Twitter, the thing that you=
 can see on your screen when you go to Twitter.com; he didn=E2=80=99t buy T=
witter for its employees and contracts and codebase and whatever else. His =
diligence was using Twitter. Everything else was unnecessary.
Similarly, in the counterfactual where the Saudi PIF invested tens of billi=
ons of dollars in Elon Musk=E2=80=99s proposal to take Tesla private, there=
 was no reason for them to tour a factory and examine the contracts Tesla u=
sed to pre-sell cars. The diligence there is, you look at Tesla=E2=80=99s f=
inancial statements
  [4]
 and public filings and conclude that this is a plausible company, and then=
 you talk to Elon Musk and decide whether or not you believe in his vision =
and trust him to achieve it. Sure PIF probably=C2=A0would=C2=A0have done so=
me diligence, because it employs professionals and they do stuff like that,=
 but I=E2=80=99m not sure it would have mattered.
  [5]

My general view is that Elon Musk   does not know how mergers work, but I d=
on=E2=80=99t really mean that in a bad way. Musk is interesting because he =
is clever, forceful, a good pitchman, and not at all interested in how thin=
gs are supposed to be done. Back when he was fighting to get out of the Twi=
tter deal, a lot of people who=C2=A0do=C2=A0know how mergers work =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0me among them =E2=80=94=C2=A0were pretty nervous. What if he=C2=A0did=
=C2=A0succeed in getting out of that deal, for basically no reason at all, =
just because he wanted to and was shameless? It didn=E2=80=99t seem impossi=
ble, and it would totally upend how mergers and acquisitions work. All of t=
he mechanics of merger agreements would have to be rethought, if Musk found=
 a new way to blow them up.
He ended up failing there, but he has succeeded in other places. Musk had T=
esla buy another company he owned, Solar City Corp., in a bizarrely conflic=
ted transaction. There are standard ways to do conflicted transactions like=
 that to make sure they are fair to both sets of shareholders, and Musk mos=
tly ignored them. Shareholders sued, and   the judge was mildly exasperated=
 that Musk didn=E2=80=99t know how mergers work.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI=C2=A0canno=
t help but observe that Elon (and the rest of the Tesla Board members) like=
ly could have avoided this expensive and time-consuming litigation had they=
 just adopted more objectively evident procedural protections,=E2=80=9D he =
wrote. But he ruled for Musk anyway. Musk didn=E2=80=99t know how mergers w=
ere supposed to work, so he did it his way, and that=E2=80=99s how mergers =
work now.
I don=E2=80=99t really think that Musk=E2=80=99s 2018 tweets about maybe ta=
king Tesla private will revolutionize the practice of leveraged buyouts, or=
 really=C2=A0of CEO tweeting. But I do think that the real objection=C2=A0=
=E2=80=94=C2=A0from the SEC, from shareholders, from me =E2=80=94=C2=A0to t=
hose tweets is not so much =E2=80=9Cthis is securities fraud designed to de=
ceive investors and enrich Musk=E2=80=9D
  [6]
=C2=A0as it is =E2=80=9Cyou are just not supposed to do that, this is not h=
ow CEOs behave.=E2=80=9D But Musk doesn=E2=80=99t care about how he=E2=80=
=99s supposed to behave, and often that works out for him.

 =20
   =20
      Americanas
   =20
 =20

I   wrote last week about the rapid collapse of FTX Trading Ltd.:

Imagine that you were magically installed as chief executive officer of FTX=
 in, say, late October of 2022,=C2=A0after=C2=A0Alameda borrowed/lost/stole=
 billions of dollars of customer money, but=C2=A0before=C2=A0people noticed=
 and demanded their money back. And your staff came to you and described th=
e whole situation in accurate detail, and then asked you what you wanted to=
 do. Your basic choices were:
=09Announce =E2=80=9Chey, turns out the previous management misplaced billi=
ons of dollars of customer money, we=E2=80=99re looking into it, sorry abou=
t that.=E2=80=9D And then try to fill the hole as rapidly as possible =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0by selling cryptocurrency or real estate, by begging to take ba=
ck donations, by finding new outside investors, etc.=C2=A0=09Announce =E2=
=80=9CFTX is stronger than ever,=E2=80=9D reassure customers that everythin=
g is great,=C2=A0and launch=C2=A0a new ad campaign to attract more deposits=
.


I know what I=E2=80=99d choose! If you are an outside candidate magically i=
nstalled as CEO of a company that has been doing fraud, Option 1 almost cer=
tainly avoids=C2=A0personal criminal liability. Not going to prison would b=
e my top priority in any sort of high-finance job, so I would quickly annou=
nce my predecessors' fraud.
On the other hand I do want to recognize that Option 2=C2=A0might=C2=A0be b=
etter for customers and shareholders: You buy yourself some time to make pr=
ofits and possibly get out of the hole created by the fraud, albeit at the =
cost of committing more fraud. I don=E2=80=99t recommend it or anything =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0most of the time, trying to earn your way out of fraud just mak=
es things worse =E2=80=94=C2=A0and if you are not already part of the fraud=
, it seems pretty insane to jump in and participate. But it would be kind o=
f an interesting move. Whereas Option 1 blows up the firm immediately: FTX =
is a levered financial institution funded by customer deposits that can (in=
 theory!) be withdrawn at any time, so announcing that it=E2=80=99s a big f=
raud leads to an immediate run on the bank and bankruptcy.
Weirdly Sergio Rial found himself in more or less this exact situation, but=
 at a retailer.   He chose Option 1:

Hours after revealing a scandal that would roil Brazilian markets, Sergio R=
ial joined a Zoom call with hundreds of panicked investors. It was an attem=
pt to explain the $4 billion accounting gap that pushed him to quit his new=
 job at the helm of retailer=C2=A0Americanas SA. =E2=80=A6
Within a week, the company filed for bankruptcy protection with $8.2 billio=
n of debt. ...
It was a sharp reversal for a company that had seen its stock rally after R=
ial was named chief executive officer last August, a job he only started on=
 Jan. 2. Investors thought Americanas, which has been backed by billionaire=
s Jorge Paulo Lemann, Marcel Telles and Carlos Alberto Sicupira for more th=
an four decades, was set for improved performance under the 62-year-old for=
mer banker=E2=80=99s leadership.=C2=A0
It unraveled on the night of Jan. 11 when it announced =E2=80=9Cinconsisten=
cies=E2=80=9D that had artificially boosted profits and reduced reported li=
abilities by half. The company=E2=80=99s disclosures imply it misreported n=
umbers tied to financing of debts with suppliers while also wrongly deducti=
ng interest paid to lenders from its liabilities.
In the Thursday bankruptcy protection filing =E2=80=94 similar to a Chapter=
 11 in the US =E2=80=94 lawyers for the company said, =E2=80=9Cdue to unexp=
ected reasons that rocked the group=E2=80=99s structure, the petitioners sa=
w their cash and revenue expectations crumble within minutes.=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0Wall Street analysts quickly put their ratings under review and=
 ratings firms downgraded the debt, after which banks refused to advance cr=
edit card receivables, draining more than 3 billion reais from the company=
=E2=80=99s cash.=C2=A0

You might naively assume that a big retailer would=C2=A0not=C2=A0be subject=
 to a run on the bank: You announce =E2=80=9Chey we did a lot of fraud,=E2=
=80=9D the stock goes down, but you still have the same stores and inventor=
y and brand as you did the day before, customers keep showing up at your st=
ores and buying stuff, and maybe you cut costs and earn enough to fill the =
hole in your accounts. Sure you have some long-term debt, and sure the lend=
ers say you are in default and demand their money back, but you can fight t=
hat in court for a while. It=E2=80=99s not like you have depositors who can=
 take out all their money at the first hint of fraud.
But a lesson here is that, deep down,=C2=A0lots of companies are actually l=
evered financial institutions subject to run risk. Americanas doesn=E2=80=
=99t just sell stuff to customers for money that it=C2=A0uses to pay for mo=
re stuff; it sells stuff to customers on credit and then borrows against th=
e receivables to pay its bills. It funds itself with short-term borrowing, =
that could dry up overnight, and did.=C2=A0Because it did a fraud, and beca=
use it=C2=A0told=C2=A0everyone.

