   =20
      Do the partners at Cravath, Swaine & Moore do a ritual chant at one a=
nother=E2=80=99s=C2=A0funerals?
   =20
 =20

No, though it would be amazing if they did. There is a claim floating aroun=
d that, at a Cravath partner=E2=80=99s funeral, there is =E2=80=9Ca process=
ion of past and present partners,=E2=80=9D who chant=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe part=
ner is dead, the firm lives.=E2=80=9D I   wrote once:
Would you ... want ... that? You'd be dead, of course, so you wouldn't care=
, but why would the families allow it? "Next up in the service: Harry's wor=
k buddies are gonna chant ominously=C2=A0for a while." It's like John Grish=
am meets Dan Brown. I hope they wear hooded robes for their chant.
I was skeptical that this actually happened, and here is a  thorough invest=
igation from Dan Stone debunking it. =C2=A0=E2=80=9CThere is no such chant,=
 nor has there ever been,=E2=80=9D says Cravath=E2=80=99s head of communica=
tions. There is a procession, =E2=80=9Cif the family wishes,=E2=80=9D and t=
he story about the chant seems to involve a misunderstanding about that: A =
1993 New Yorker story described the procession and said that the partners=
=E2=80=99 =E2=80=9Cen-banc presence announced, as it had on so many occasio=
ns in the past, =E2=80=98A partner has died; the firm lives.=E2=80=99=E2=80=
=9D I am not sure that=E2=80=99s quite right =E2=80=94=C2=A0you might inter=
pret the procession to mean =E2=80=9Cwe liked spending time with our work b=
uddy and want to pay our final respects=E2=80=9D rather than =E2=80=9Cour F=
irm can never die=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but even if it is, their=C2=A0pre=
sence announced it.=C2=A0They=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t announce it. That would b=
e weird.

