  [1] The stock split twice since then,  5 for 1 and  3 for 1, meaning that=
 $420 per share in 2018 translates into $28 per share today; the stock clos=
ed yesterday at $143.75.


  [2] I suppose there=E2=80=99s a question of intent, except that the judge=
 also ruled that Musk was at least reckless in making these false statement=
s, which is the requisite scienter for this action, so practically speaking=
 it doesn=E2=80=99t matter if Musk *thought* he had funding secured =E2=80=
=94 if he did, he thought it recklessly, and can still be liable.


  [3] It=E2=80=99s not just hostile deals, though. Warren Buffett notably d=
oes not do much traditional due diligence when he buys companies. When he b=
uys companies and it doesn=E2=80=99t work out,  he has said, the mistakes a=
re =E2=80=9Cnot a bad lease. They=E2=80=99re not a specific labor contract.=
 They=E2=80=99re not a questionable patent. They=E2=80=99re not the things =
that are on the checklist, you know, for every acquisition by every major c=
orporation in America. Those are not the things that count. =E2=80=A6 We ha=
ve not found a due diligence list that gets at what we think are the real r=
isks when we buy a business.=E2=80=9D More generally if you are a public st=
ock investor =E2=80=94 if you regularly buy and sell large chunks of public=
ly traded stocks, as Buffett sort of does, and as various activist hedge fu=
nd managers do, etc. =E2=80=94 then you are used to evaluating companies ba=
sed on public information, and nervous about taking nonpublic information f=
rom management that would restrict your ability to trade. And so sometimes =
you make very large share purchases =E2=80=94 sometimes of 100% of the comp=
any =E2=80=94 without nonpublic due diligence.


  [4] In 2018, they showed that Tesla had lost money every year, by the way=
. That changed! Again, betting on Tesla in 2018 would have worked out reall=
y well, for Musk or the PIF or anyone else.


  [5] Famously, PIF=E2=80=99s investment professionals did some due diligen=
ce on  Jared Kushner=E2=80=99s investment firm and advised PIF=E2=80=99s bo=
ard to pass; the board invested anyway. That investment is not about a due =
diligence checklist!


  [6] There is an idea, in the SEC and class action complaints about those =
tweets, that Musk hates short sellers and so pretended to take Tesla privat=
e in order to harm short sellers. This theory strikes me as absurd: Sure he=
 hates short sellers, but the nonsense about taking Tesla private probably =
mostly *helped* them.


