<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two small points on Musk=E2=80=99s testimony. =
First, here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/303=
47296.266447/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZjY0ZTMyMTQtZjk0Zi00NjJiLT=
kwYTQtZTlkMzVkNzE0M2Rh/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBecc5651f" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the Fina=
ncial Times</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nicholas Porritt, a lawyer for sha=
reholders, pointed out Musk did not discuss any proposal in advance with Te=
sla=E2=80=99s board of directors. But the billionaire said that would be im=
proper: =E2=80=9CI, as the bidder, am not allowed to have detailed discussi=
ons with the board because it represents the counterparty. So, it would be =
collusion if I discussed in detail with the board.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a weird view? Most management buyouts =
begin with the chief executive officer approaching the board of directors a=
nd suggesting a deal, and discussions get pretty far along before there is =
a public announcement. (Also, back in August 2018, <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30347296.266447/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGVzbGEuY2=
9tL2Jsb2cvdXBkYXRlLXRha2luZy10ZXNsYS1wcml2YXRl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc0b=
2d84f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;"> Musk </a><em><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/30347296.266447/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGVzbGEuY29tL2Jsb2cvdXBkYXRlLXRh=
a2luZy10ZXNsYS1wcml2YXRl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCc0b2d84f" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">said</a=
>=C2=A0</em>that he had had discussions with the board about his proposal, =
including the price and financing, before tweeting it.) It=E2=80=99s not co=
llusion to negotiate a deal with a counterparty; it=E2=80=99s just =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0negotiation. That said, you can understand his instinct that there=
 is something weird and conflicted about the CEO of a public company negoti=
ating with its board to buy it for himself. It happens, fairly often, but i=
t is a necessarily sensitive situation. He=E2=80=99s not wrong that, in som=
e sense, it is=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>disclosure to give shareholders some=
 early warning about what is going on. It is just not traditional.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/30347296.266447/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXhpb3MuY29tL25l=
d3NsZXR0ZXJzL2F4aW9zLXByby1yYXRhLTE4ZWY5ZDNkLTdiYzctNDY5MC04NGUwLTgyOTdiMjc=
1YTNkNC5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfde6cd7f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Dan Primack at Ax=
ios this morning</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Musk] also reiterated his odd vie=
w of due diligence, as evidenced throughout the Twitter saga, in claiming t=
hat the Saudis didn't need to do any prior to Musk making a formal takeover=
 offer because Tesla was a public company (i.e., it already had access to a=
ll the information it would need).</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I want to defend Musk a little bit here. Yes, =
this is absolutely an=C2=A0<em>odd=C2=A0</em>view of due diligence. Most pe=
ople, in the course of doing or funding $60 billion leveraged buyouts, want=
 to do some non-public due diligence on the target company. They want to lo=
ok at its financial plans and talk to its customers and employees and read =
its contracts and generally understand the company in more depth than they =
could get from its public filings.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it is not unheard-of to buy a public compa=
ny without due diligence.=C2=A0In particular, if you are going to make a=C2=
=A0<em>hostile=C2=A0</em>takeover offer for a company =E2=80=94=C2=A0by tak=
ing a tender offer directly to shareholders instead of negotiating with the=
 board of directors =E2=80=94=C2=A0you have to be willing to do it without =
any cooperation from existing management.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> That is what Musk proposed to Twitter, and while the deal ultimately b=
ecame friendly, he never did do due diligence. Also it makes sense! He foll=
owed up by getting rid of 80% of employees, torching Twitter=E2=80=99s adve=
rtising business, unplugging data centers, selling the office espresso mach=
ines, etc. In a sense he bought Twitter to own=C2=A0<em>Twitter</em>, the t=
hing that you can see on your screen when you go to Twitter.com; he didn=E2=
=80=99t buy Twitter for its employees and contracts and codebase and whatev=
er else. His diligence was using Twitter. Everything else was unnecessary.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly, in the counterfactual where the Sau=
di PIF invested tens of billions of dollars in Elon Musk=E2=80=99s proposal=
 to take Tesla private, there was no reason for them to tour a factory and =
examine the contracts Tesla used to pre-sell cars. The diligence there is, =
you look at Tesla=E2=80=99s financial statements<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> and public filings and conclude that this is a plausible company, and =
then you talk to Elon Musk and decide whether or not you believe in his vis=
ion and trust him to achieve it. Sure PIF probably=C2=A0<em>would=C2=A0</em=
>have done some diligence, because it employs professionals and they do stu=
ff like that, but I=E2=80=99m not sure it would have mattered.<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My general view is that Elon Musk <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30347296.266447/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMDcvZG9lcy1lbG9uLW11c=
2sta25vdy1ob3ctbWVyZ2Vycy13b3JrP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjQyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9t=
ZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDEyNCZ1dG1fY2F=
tcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4fa754bd" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  does n=
ot know how mergers work</a>, but I don=E2=80=99t really mean that in a bad=
 way. Musk is interesting because he is clever, forceful, a good pitchman, =
and not at all interested in how things are supposed to be done. Back when =
he was fighting to get out of the Twitter deal, a lot of people who=C2=A0<e=
m>do=C2=A0</em>know how mergers work =E2=80=94=C2=A0me among them =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0were pretty nervous. What if he=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>succeed in get=
ting out of that deal, for basically no reason at all, just because he want=
ed to and was shameless? It didn=E2=80=99t seem impossible, and it would to=
tally upend how mergers and acquisitions work. All of the mechanics of merg=
er agreements would have to be rethought, if Musk found a new way to blow t=
hem up.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He ended up failing there, but he has succeede=
d in other places. Musk had Tesla buy another company he owned, Solar City =
Corp., in a bizarrely conflicted transaction. There are standard ways to do=
 conflicted transactions like that to make sure they are fair to both sets =
of shareholders, and Musk mostly ignored them. Shareholders sued, and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30347296.266447/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMjgvZWxvbi1tdX=
NrLXMtb3RoZXItbWVyZ2VyLXdvcmtlZC1vdXQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEyNDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmd=
XRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTI0JnV0=
bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf7f9cc17" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  t=
he judge was mildly exasperated</a> that Musk didn=E2=80=99t know how merge=
rs work.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI=C2=A0cannot help but observe that Elon (and the re=
st of the Tesla Board members) likely could have avoided this expensive and=
 time-consuming litigation had they just adopted more objectively evident p=
rocedural protections,=E2=80=9D he wrote. But he ruled for Musk anyway. Mus=
k didn=E2=80=99t know how mergers were supposed to work, so he did it his w=
ay, and that=E2=80=99s how mergers work now.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t really think that Musk=E2=80=
=99s 2018 tweets about maybe taking Tesla private will revolutionize the pr=
actice of leveraged buyouts, or really=C2=A0of CEO tweeting. But I do think=
 that the real objection=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0from the SEC, from shareholder=
s, from me =E2=80=94=C2=A0to those tweets is not so much =E2=80=9Cthis is s=
ecurities fraud designed to deceive investors and enrich Musk=E2=80=9D<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0as it is =E2=80=9Cyou are just not supposed to do that, this is n=
ot how CEOs behave.=E2=80=9D But Musk doesn=E2=80=99t care about how he=E2=
=80=99s supposed to behave, and often that works out for him.</p>
